column168: UPON ROUTINE INSPECTION AT A TRUCK STOP NEAR GUYMON, OKLAHOMA, THE DRIVER N OTICED A SMALL LEAK FROM THE REAR FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE TRAILER TO CONTAIN THE DRIP. THE DRIVER REPORTED TO THE U NDERSIGNED. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY. THE U.S.C.G. WAS NOTIFIED . AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS DISPATCHED OUR OF OKLAHOMA CITY. THE TEAM OVERPACKED THE LEAKERS AND CLEANED THE AREAS OF CONTAMINATION. THE LOAD WAS THEN DELIVERED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

88 DRUMS OF WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID WEREPRE-LOADED BY CWMI CARLYSS, LOUISIA NA TSD FACILITY AND OFFERED TO CWMI TRANSPORTATION FOR SHIPMENT. THE DRIVER THAT PICKED UP THE LOADED TRAILER WAS ALLOWED ONLY TO INSPECT HIS LOAD FRO M THE GROUND OUTSIDE OF THE VAN DUE TO COMPANY RESTRICTIONS OF ENTERING CON FINED SPACES. THIS INSPECTION ONLY ALLOWED A LIMITED VIEW OF THE CARGO, TH EREFORE, NO INDICATIONS OF A PROBLEM WITH THE LEAKING DRUM WERE SPOTTED, IF EVEN APPEARANT. WHILE DOING A PRE-TRIP INSPECTION OF HIS VEHICLE AFTER AN 8 HOUR BREAK THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT LIQUID WAS LEAKING FROM THE FLOOR AND DOOR AREA OF THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED HIS HOME TERMINAL AND A CWMI RESPONSE CREW WAS SENT OUT WHICH UNDERTOOK ALL REMEDIAL ACTION AND PREPARED THE TRAILER FOR TRANSPORTATION BACK TO THE POINT OF ORIGIN WHI CH WAS APPROX. 8 MILES AWAY. PACKAGING PREPARATIONS AND LOADING PROCEDURES ARE BEING INVESTIGATED FOR POSSIBLE PROBLEM AREAS WHICH MAY HAVE CONTRIBUTE D TO THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT, I.E., DAMAGING OF GASKET WHEN ASSEMBLED AND POSSIBLE OVERFILLING OF CONTAINER. THE USE OF A PROTECTIVE LINER ON THE FL OOR OF VANS HAS BEEN SUGGESTED AND IN PROCESS OF BEING RESEARCHED.

column168: PACKAGE WAS LOADED ON PACKAGE CAR SHELF. AT THIS TIME THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE. DRIVER MADE DELIVERIES AND NOTICED THERE WAS SOME WET PACKAGES AND TOUCHING THEM CAUSED HIS HANDS TO BURN A LITTLE. HE THEN INSPECTED THE ENTIRE SHELF, AND FOUND THE WET BOX. HE REMOVED FROM THE SHELF AND DOING S O CAUSED THE CONTAINER INSIDE TO SPLASH. THE ACID SPILLED ON HIS HANDS CAUS ING THEM TO BLISTER. ALSO IT SPLASHED IN HIS EYES CAUSING A SEVERE BURNING SENSATION. THE DRIVER CALLED US AND REPORTED THE INCIDENT. WE THEN TOOK THE DRIVER TO THE HOSPITAL FOR TREATMENT. PACKAGE WAS PACKED ACCORDING TO HAZA RDOUS MATERIAL PROCEDURES. 4 EA 5 QT. PLASTIC CONTAINERS IN CARTON ALSO 4 8 OZ. PLASTIC BOTTLES STUCK IN CARTON. NO DIVIDERS, NO PACKING MAT., LIDS NOT SEALED. INSPECTED BY CUSTOMERS SERVICE REPRESENTATIVE SUSAN ALLEN.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0345 HUB 0PERATIONS NOTIFIED MYSELF OF A POSSIBLE HAZ-MAT SPILL IN D-2 (A SPECIFIC BUILD-UP AREA WITHIN THE WAREHOUSE). UPON ARRIVING AT THE SCENE, I DISCOVERED A PLAIN BROWN BOX THAT WAS WET WITH AN UNKNOWN SUBSTANCE AND A 5 GALLON METAL PAIL SITTING BESIDE THE FIBERBOARD CONTAINER WITH A SPONTANEOUSLY COMBUSTIBLE LABEL ATTACHED. THE LABEL WAS DISCOVERED ON THE INNER CONTAINER BY ONE OF EMERY'S REPACKAGING PERSONNEL. HE WAS IN T HE PROCESS OF RECOUPING THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX WHEN HE DISCOVERED THE INN ER METAL PAIL HAD A SPONTANEOUSLY COMBUSTIBLE LABEL ATTACHED. THIS IS WHEN THE AREA WAS EVACUATED AND THE APPROPRIATE PERSONNEL WAS NOTIFIED OF A POSS IBLE HAZ-MAT SSPILL. APPEARS THE REASON FOR THE SPILL WAS THE RESULT OF A L OOSE FITTING CLOSURE ON THE INNER RECEPTACLES. MICHAEL A. MASSIE ON 8-13-87 WE HAD A RECOUP IN MODULE D. WE ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 0340. W E WENT TO RECOUP THE BOX AND THE FIVE GALLON METAL PAIL INSIDE STARTED TO L EAK OUR OF THE BOX. THE BOX DID NOT HAVE A HAZ-MAT LABEL ON IT. AFTER THE P AIL STARTED LEAKING WE PULLED THE PAIL OUT OT THE BOX. WE THEN DISCOVERED T HE FIVE GALLON METAL PAIL HAD A HAZ-MAT LABEL ON IT (SPONTANEOUSLY COMBUSTI BLE). WE THEN EVACUATED THE AREA AND CALLED HUB OPERATIONS THAT WE HAD A PO SSIBLE HAZ-MAT SPILL IN THE D MODULE.   TOM CASONI
